            <section class="mt-8 prose">
              <h2>How the tennis Elo rating works</h2>
              <p>
                Elo is a rating system that estimates a player’s underlying
                strength and uses it to predict match outcomes. After every
                match, the winner gains points and the loser loses points.
                Upsets (when an underdog wins) cause bigger rating changes than
                expected results.
              </p>

              <h3>Core Elo formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Expected win probability</p>
                <p>
                  Let \( R_A \) and \( R_B \) be the current Elo ratings of
                  Player A and Player B. The expected score (win probability)
                  for Player A is:
                </p>
                <p>\[ E_A = \frac{1}{1 + 10^{(R_B - R_A)/400}} \]</p>
                <p>Similarly, for Player B:</p>
                <p>\[ E_B = 1 - E_A \]</p>
                <hr class="my-2" />
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Rating update after the match</p>
                <p>
                  Let \( S_A \) be the actual score for Player A (1 = win, 0 =
                  loss, 0.5 = draw). The new rating is:
                </p>
                <p>\[ R'_A = R_A + K \cdot (S_A - E_A) \]</p>
                <p>
                  \(K\) is the <strong>K‑factor</strong>, which controls how
                  fast ratings move. The same formula applies to Player B with
                  \(S_B = 1 - S_A\).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Choosing a K‑factor for tennis</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>20–24:</strong> Very stable ratings, good for
                  established pros with lots of data.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>32:</strong> Balanced choice for most club players and
                  general use.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>40+:</strong> Very reactive, useful for juniors, new
                  players, or short seasons.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In this calculator you can pick a preset or define your own
                K‑factor, and then scale it for
                <strong>match importance</strong> (Grand Slam vs. exhibition)
                and <strong>score margin</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>Surface and context adjustments</h3>
              <p>
                One of the main criticisms of a single Elo rating in tennis is
                that it ignores
                <strong>surface differences</strong> and context (best‑of‑3 vs.
                best‑of‑5, altitude, indoor vs. outdoor, etc.). Advanced models
                often maintain separate Elo ratings for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Hard courts</li>
                <li>Clay</li>
                <li>Grass</li>
                <li>Indoor vs. outdoor</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you want to go that route, simply keep three parallel Elo
                values for each player and update only the relevant one after
                each match. This tool’s surface and importance multipliers give
                you a lightweight way to approximate that behaviour without
                managing multiple full rating tables.
              </p>

              <h3>Interpreting Elo differences in tennis</h3>
              <p>Some useful benchmarks for Elo differences:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>0 points:</strong> 50%–50% match, true coin flip.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>100 points:</strong> ~64% win probability for the
                  higher‑rated player.
                </li>
                <li><strong>200 points:</strong> ~76% win probability.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>400 points:</strong> ~91% win probability (big
                  favourite).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These probabilities are <em>pre‑match expectations</em>. Upsets
                still happen frequently in tennis, especially in best‑of‑3
                formats or on fast surfaces.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for using tennis Elo ratings</h2>
              <h3>1. Starting ratings</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  For a new closed group (e.g., a club ladder), start everyone
                  at the same rating (e.g., 1500).
                </li>
                <li>
                  For juniors entering an existing pool, start them slightly
                  below average and use a higher K‑factor.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For historical analysis, you can backfill ratings from an
                  initial season using real match data.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Handling retirements, walkovers, and defaults</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Walkover / no play:</strong> Many analysts choose
                  <em>no Elo update</em>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Retirement mid‑match:</strong> You can either treat it
                  as a normal win/loss or apply a reduced K.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Disqualifications:</strong> Usually treated as a
                  normal result, but you may prefer a smaller K.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Using Elo for predictions and analysis</h3>
              <p>You can use tennis Elo ratings to:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Estimate win probabilities for betting or fantasy contests.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compare players across eras (with caution about baselines).
                </li>
                <li>Track form over time and identify hot or cold streaks.</li>
                <li>
                  Build more advanced models that combine Elo with serve/return
                  stats.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is a good Elo rating in tennis?</h3>
              <p>
                There is no universal scale, but as a rough guide in many
                implementations: recreational players are around 1200–1600,
                strong club players 1700–2000, and elite pros above 2200–2600.
                Focus more on <strong>differences</strong> than absolute values.
              </p>

              <h3>How is tennis Elo different from ATP or WTA rankings?</h3>
              <p>
                ATP/WTA rankings are based on tournament points over the last 52
                weeks and are designed for entry and seeding. Elo is a
                statistical rating that updates after every match and is
                optimized for <strong>predicting future results</strong>. A
                player can be rising fast in Elo before their official ranking
                catches up.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this calculator for doubles?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, but you should decide whether you rate
                <strong>individual players</strong> or
                <strong>fixed teams</strong>. For teams, treat each pair as a
                single “player” with its own rating.
              </p>

              <h3>Why do some analysts criticize Elo in tennis?</h3>
              <p>
                Common criticisms include ignoring surface, match format,
                injuries, and scheduling effects. Elo also assumes independence
                between matches and a constant underlying strength, which is not
                always true in real life. Still, with sensible tweaks
                (surface‑specific ratings, context‑dependent K), Elo remains one
                of the most practical and interpretable rating systems for
                tennis.
              </p>
